    short_description: "Discourse that critically reflects and questions the topics is an important part of learning. \nIt is the responsibility of the instructor to *facilitate* discourse for maintaining interest, \nstudent engagement and motivation and to support students’ understanding. Facilitating discourse includes all activities / postings of the instructor that “stimulate social process with a direct goal of stimulating individual and group learning” (Anderson et al., 2001)\n**In online teaching and learning, online students must have equal opportunities to participate, \nto interact and understand concepts and topics of the teaching material.**\n",
    titles_accordion: "Online Course Requirements",
    content_accordion: "1. Online students must have an opportunity to ask questions and have a clear and reliable \nexpectation about when and how to get an answer.\n2. If you do synchronous sessions, you must allow online participation. Synchronous sessions \nalways exclude some students. Alternative time slots are optimal and you should expect the study \ncommission to ask you to move to a different time slot.\n3. It must be possible for online students to work in a group with on-site students if there \nare group assignments.",
